#!/bin/bash
set -euxo pipefail

export PATH="/root/.local/bin:$PATH"
cd /root/quacksync

./start-stack.sh

uv run python -m quacksync.flow

cat > notes.md <<'EOF'
# QuackSync baseline notes

## Stage classifications
- fetch: I/O-bound. It's an HTTP call to the Duck Catalog API. The CPU is mostly idle while we wait for the response.
- enrich: I/O-bound. Another HTTP call, this time to a rate-limited API, so it will also interact with limits later.
- score: CPU-bound. It's a tight NumPy loop against a fixed reference matrix with no I/O at all.
- write: I/O-bound. It executes a single UPSERT through a connection-pool-limited SQLite wrapper.

## Prediction
Parallelism will help fetch and enrich the most because they spend their time waiting on network I/O, so running multiple at once costs almost nothing extra. Threading should be enough there. Scoring is CPU-bound, so threads won't help much because of the GIL - we'll want a process pool. Writes look cheap today, but once the other stages fan out we'll suddenly try to open dozens of connections through a pool of 5, which is where I expect the first new problem to appear.
EOF
